Let's _practice_ with _carrots_. They're _inexpensive_. And no matter how many you cut up while practicing, you'll eat them eventually.

First, _peel_ a _carrot_ and _cut_ it into two or three _finger-length_ pieces.

When you're working with _round vegetables_, there's a _danger_ of the object _rolling under_ your _free hand_, accidentally _exposing_ your _fingers_ to the _moving knife_'s edge. We _avoid this_ by _flattening_ or “squaring off”. You can do this by _cutting_ the _carrot pieces_ in _half lengthwise_, or just cutting a small strip off, so it _lays flat_ on the board.

